{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17631084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17631084"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:23:31+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:23:31+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17349"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17349","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17349"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.8,0.1,0,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10039"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78686"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10039","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10039"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17349"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64029"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"6798"},{"type":"tags","id":"6808"},{"type":"tags","id":"6814"},{"type":"tags","id":"6815"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23502"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23599"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78686"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pleural cavity is the space between the lungs and chest wall.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the normal structure of the pleural cavity?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Thin layer of lubricating fluid separating inner and outer pleural membranes","Gas-filled anatomical space located between pulmonary tissue and thoracic wall","Lymph-containing channel encircling the bronchial tree","Serous cavity situated between cardiac and pulmonary tissues","Fibrous membrane connecting lung segments to chest wall"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe pleural cavity is a \u003Cstrong\u003Ethin layer of lubricating fluid separating inner and outer pleural membranes\u003C/strong\u003E. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis cavity is the space between the visceral pleura, the inner layer that adheres tightly to the lung surface, and the parietal pleura, the outer layer that attaches to the chest wall, diaphragm, and mediastinum. Between these layers is a thin film of serous fluid that reduces friction during respiratory movements.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGas-filled anatomical space located between pulmonary tissue and thoracic wall\u003C/strong\u003E - Air in the pleural space (pneumothorax) is abnormal and causes lung collapse\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELymph-containing channel encircling the bronchial tree\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the lymphatic vessels situated around airways, not the pleural space\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerous cavity situated between cardiac and pulmonary tissues\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the pericardial space around the heart\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFibrous membrane connecting lung segments to chest wall\u003C/strong\u003E - The pleural space contains fluid, not fibrous tissue, and the membranes are not directly connected\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe pleural cavity assists in maintaining the slight negative pressure that helps keep the lungs inflated. The small amount of pleural fluid acts as a lubricant, allowing the two pleural layers to slide smoothly past each other during breathing without friction.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The pleural cavity is a potential space between the visceral and parietal pleura that contains a small amount of lubricating serous fluid.","The visceral pleura covers the surface of the lungs while the parietal pleura lines the chest wall, mediastinum, and diaphragm.","Negative pressure within the pleural space helps maintain lung inflation during normal breathing."],"references":["Netter FH. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: A Regional Approach with Latin Terminology. Eighth edition. Elsevier; 2022.","Drake R. Gray\u2019s Atlas of Anatomy. 3rd ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021.","\u201cIllustration from Anatomy \u0026 Physiology, Connexions Web site\u201d by OpenStax College is licensed under\u00a0Creative Commons\u00a0Attribution-Share Alike 3.0 Unported\u00a0license. (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0) \u003Chttps://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:2313_The_Lung_Pleurea.jpg\u003E"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64029"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17349"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21307"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21307","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21307"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZL3iIbcqGNLJc9ghYDjGdZbiKGCqB7.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/ZL3iIbcqGNLJc9ghYDjGdZbiKGCqB7.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":482}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64029","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64029"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T08:35:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T08:36:13+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10039"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78686"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"t